<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-177-732  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 177 732.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Canadian Datasystems  March 1989 v21 n3 p58(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Graphics float in space. (BBN Systems and Technologies Corp'sSpaceGraph three-dimensional display system) (includes relatedarticle on the utility of a third dimension)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Weissman, Tom.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>BBN Systems and Technologies Corp is billing its new SpaceGraphsystem as a technology advance in the field of three-dimensional(3D) display.andP;  SpaceGraph displays the visual equivalent of aphysical model, and does it without holography or with the needfor special glasses.andP;  The model appears to float in space so thatcurves and holes look real and depth is unmistakable.andP;  The systemuses a mirror that becomes concave and convex alternately.andP;  Userssee an XY monitor in the mirror, which seems to swing toward andaway from the viewer.andP;  The software provided with the systemcombines input data with optical data to feed to the monitor.andP;  Thelarge table-top display device can be used in conjunction with anIBM AT or RT personal computer.andP;  The system is particularly usefulwith CAE (computer-aided engineering) applications.andP;  A basicsystem costs $35,000.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   BBN Systems and Technologies Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   BBN Systems and Technologies SpaceGraph (Computer graphicsmonitor) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     TechnologyGraphics TerminalsThree-Dimensional Graphics.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographchart.andO;Caption:   (Diagram illustrating conceptual oscillation). (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>